\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {10}{\ignorespaces The shift map on the circle. Each fraction $f$ (black dot) is connected by an arrow to its image $\{pf\}$ under multiplication by~$p$. \textbf  {Left:} prime $p = 7$ scrambles all fractions. \textbf  {Right:} composite $N = 6$ has fewer arrows (missing fractions with $\gcd (k,6) > 1$). The scrambling by primes is what decorrelates the rank discrepancy from the fractional part $\left \{pf\right \}$.}}{13}{figure.10}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:shift-map}{{10}{13}{The shift map on the circle. Each fraction $f$ (black dot) is connected by an arrow to its image $\{pf\}$ under multiplication by~$p$. \textbf {Left:} prime $p = 7$ scrambles all fractions. \textbf {Right:} composite $N = 6$ has fewer arrows (missing fractions with $\gcd (k,6) > 1$). The scrambling by primes is what decorrelates the rank discrepancy from the fractional part $\fpart {pf}$}{figure.10}{}}
